# Task {{task_key}}

## Identity
- board_item_id: {{board_item_id}}
- title: {{title}}
- status: {{status}}
- priority: {{priority}}

## Objective
{{description}}

## What To Do
- Deliver the task described above without silently narrowing the scope.
- Turn ambiguous work into explicit outputs instead of vague intent.
- Keep the work product durable inside this task workspace.

## How To Work
- Put handoffs in `/task/handoffs/`.
- Put durable artifacts in `/task/artifacts/`.
- Put working notes in `/task/notes/`.
- If `/task/RUNBOOK.md` exists, keep it small and use it only for recurring-task carry-forward facts:
  - key file or script paths
  - main data shape or storage location
  - reusable commands or procedures
  - non-obvious gotchas or invariants
- Do not turn `/task/RUNBOOK.md` into a journal.
- Reuse the existing task workspace structure instead of recreating it.
- Treat unrelated files elsewhere in `/workspace/` as out of scope unless explicitly linked.

## Deliverables
- Leave a durable handoff file when you finish a task stage.
- Make sure the handoff explains what changed, what remains, and the key file paths.

## Done Means
- The requested work is actually completed, not merely explored.
- Important constraints and gaps are called out explicitly.
- The next agent can continue from the workspace without re-deriving context.

## Good Examples
- `Write /task/handoffs/final-review.md with the exact files changed, the result, and the remaining follow-up.`
- `Store the working output in /task/artifacts/ and mention the artifact path in the handoff.`

## Bad Examples
- `done`
- `looked into it`
- `fixed some stuff`
- `leave the result only in chat without a handoff or durable artifact`
